\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Metric Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Metric Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
metric 
\series default
on a set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $d:X\times X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 which satisfies the following three properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Identity of indiscernibles) 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x,y)=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Symmetric) 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x,y)=d(y,x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Triangle Inequality) 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x,z)\leq d(x,y)+d(y,z)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z\in X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 together with a choice of a metric 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
metric space 
\series default
and is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

, or just denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 if the metric is understood from context.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Given the three axioms above, we also have 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x,y)\geq0$
\end_inset

 (positive-definitene) for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =d(x,x)\\
 & \leq d(x,y)+d(y,x)\\
 & =d(x,y)+d(x,y)\\
 & =2d(x,y).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x,y)\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 On 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
Euclidean metric 
\series default
is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{E}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=\|\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{y}\|=\sqrt{(x_{1}-y_{1})^{2}+\cdots+(x_{m}-y_{m})^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

This is the usual distance used in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, and when we speak about 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 as a metric space without specifying a metric, it's the Euclidean metric
 that is intended.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To check that 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{E}$
\end_inset

 is a metric on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, the first two conditions in the definition are obvious.
 The third condition is a consequence of the inequality 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{y}\|\le\|\mathbf{x}\|+\|\mathbf{y}\|$
\end_inset

 (replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{z}-\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

), and to show this inequality holds we will write 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\mathbf{x}\|$
\end_inset

 in terms of the dot product: 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\mathbf{x}\|^{2}=x_{1}^{2}+\cdots+x_{m}^{2}=\mathbf{x}\cdot\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, so 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\|\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{y}\|^{2} & =(\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{y})\cdot(\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{y})\\
 & =\mathbf{x}\cdot\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{x}\cdot\mathbf{y}+\mathbf{y}\cdot\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{y}\cdot\mathbf{y}\\
 & =\|\mathbf{x}\|^{2}+2\mathbf{x}\cdot\mathbf{y}+\|\mathbf{y}\|^{2}\\
 & \leq\|\mathbf{x}\|^{2}+2|\mathbf{x}\cdot\mathbf{y}|+\|\mathbf{y}\|^{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The famous Cauchy-Schwarz inequality says 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mathbf{x}\cdot\mathbf{y}|\leq\|\mathbf{x}\|\|\mathbf{y}\|$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{y}\|^{2}\leq\|\mathbf{x}\|^{2}+2\|\mathbf{x}\|\|\mathbf{y}\|+\|\mathbf{y}\|^{2}=(\|\mathbf{x}\|+\|\mathbf{y}\|)^{2}
\]

\end_inset

and now take square roots.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A different metric on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{\infty}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=\max_{1\leq i\leq m}|x_{i}-y_{i}|.
\]

\end_inset

Again, the first two conditions of being a metric are clear, and to check
 the triangle inequality we use the fact that it is known for the absolute
 value.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\max|x_{i}-y_{i}|=|x_{k}-y_{k}|$
\end_inset

 for a particular 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 from
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\infty}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=|x_{k}-y_{k}|$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d_{\infty}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}) & \leq|x_{k}-z_{k}|+|z_{k}-y_{k}|\\
 & \leq\max_{1\leq i\leq m}|x_{i}-z_{i}|+\max_{1\leq i\leq m}|z_{i}-y_{i}|\\
 & =d_{\infty}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})+d_{\infty}(\mathbf{z},\mathbf{y}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

While the metrics 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{E}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 are different, they're not that different from each other since each is
 bounded by a constant multiple of the other one: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{E}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\leq\sqrt{m}d_{\infty}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\text{ and }d_{\infty}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\leq d_{E}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{examplecontinuous01}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $C[0,1]$
\end_inset

 be the space of all continuous functions from 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Two metrics used on 
\begin_inset Formula $C[0,1]$
\end_inset

 are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{\infty}(f,g)=\max_{0\leq x\leq1}|f(x)-g(x)|\text{ and }d_{1}(f,g)=\int_{0}^{1}|f(x)-g(x)|dx.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike with the two metrics on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 while we have 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1}(f,g)\leq d_{\infty}(f,g)$
\end_inset

 there is no constant 
\begin_inset Formula $A>0$
\end_inset

 that makes 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\infty}(f,g)\leq Ad_{1}(f,g)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 These metrics 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $C[0,1]$
\end_inset

 are quite different.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Metric Space Induced by a Norm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be a vector space over a subfield 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 of the complex numbers.
 A 
\series bold
norm 
\series default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is a nonnegative-valued scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $p:V\to[0,\infty)$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in V$
\end_inset

, we have 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Subadditivity) 
\begin_inset Formula $p(u+v)\leq p(u)+p(v)$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Absolutely Homogeneous) 
\begin_inset Formula $p(av)=|a|p(v)$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Positive-Definite) 
\begin_inset Formula $p(v)=0$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $v=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We call the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,p)$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
normed vector space
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,p)$
\end_inset

 be a normed vector space.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $d:V\times V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $d(u,v)=p(u-v)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(u,v)\in V\times V$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,d)$
\end_inset

 is a metric space.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let us first check that 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 satisfies the identity of indiscernibles property.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is positive-definite, 
\begin_inset Formula $d(u,v)=0$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $p(u-v)=0$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $u=v$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $u=v$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is absolutely homogeneous, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $p(0)=|0|p(0)=0$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $d(u,u)=p(0)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we check that 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is symmetric.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $(u,v)\in V\times V$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d(u,v) & =p(u-v)\\
 & =p(-1(v-u))\\
 & =|-1|p(v-u)\\
 & =p(v-u)\\
 & =d(v,u).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Finally, triangle inequality for 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 follows from subadditivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v,w\in V$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d(u,v)+d(v,w) & =p(u-v)+p(v-w)\\
 & \geq p(u-w)\\
 & =d(u,w).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The metric 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 induced by a norm 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 has additional properties that are not true of general metrics.
 These are 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Translation Invariance) 
\begin_inset Formula $d(u+w,v+w)=d(u,v)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v,w\in V$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Scaling Property) 
\begin_inset Formula $d(au,av)=|a|d(u,v)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in V$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Convserely, if a metric has these properties, then 
\begin_inset Formula $d(u,0)$
\end_inset

 is a norm.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{examplepadic}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 On 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

, we have the usual Euclidean norm 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|$
\end_inset

, but there are also other interesting norms we can put on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, for any prime 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, we can define a norm on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 called the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
adic norm
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Here's how it works: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $x=p^{k}(m/n)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is unique and 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n\in\mathbb{Z}\backslash p\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 We set 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|_{p}=p^{-k}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Limit of a Sequence in a Metric Space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 in a metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

, we say 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
converges to 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, and write 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\to\infty}x_{n}=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

, if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $N=N_{\varepsilon}\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n\geq N\text{ implies }d(x_{n},x)<\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset

If a sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 has a limit, then we say that the sequence is 
\series bold
convergent
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremconsecutive}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 in a metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 converges, then 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x_{n},x_{n+1})\to0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

.
 From the triangle inequality, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d(x_{n},x_{n+1})\leq d(x_{n},x)+d(x,x_{n+1})=d(x_{n},x)+d(x_{n+1},x).
\]

\end_inset

The two terms on the right get small when 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is large, so 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x_{n},x_{n+1})$
\end_inset

 gets small when 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is large.
 To be precise, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon/2>0$
\end_inset

 there's an 
\begin_inset Formula $N\geq1$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq N$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x_{m},x)<\varepsilon/2$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n\geq N\text{ implies }n+1\geq N\text{ implies }d(x_{n},x_{n+1})\leq d(x_{n},x)+d(x_{n+1},x)<\frac{\varepsilon}{2}+\frac{\varepsilon}{2}=\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every subsequence of a convergent sequence in a metric space is also convergent
, with the same limit.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n_{i}})$
\end_inset

 be a subsequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}=x_{n_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 We want ot show 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}\to x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x_{n},x)<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 Since the interegers 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}$
\end_inset

 are increasing, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}\geq N$
\end_inset

 if we go out far enough: there's an 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $i\geq I$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}\geq N$
\end_inset

 which imlpies 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x_{n_{i}},x)<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $d(y_{i},x)<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}\to x$
\end_inset

.
  
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In a metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

, if two sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n}')$
\end_inset

 converge to the same value, then 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x_{n},x_{n}')\to0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}'\to x$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists some integer 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n\geq N\text{ implies }d(x_{n},x)<\frac{\varepsilon}{2}\text{ and }d(x_{n}',x)<\frac{\varepsilon}{2}.
\]

\end_inset

In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n\geq N\text{ implies }d(x_{n},x_{n}')\leq d(x_{n},x)+d(x,x_{n}')<\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 On 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, because the metrics 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{E}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 are each bounded above by a constant multiple of the other, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{E}(x_{n},x)\to0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\infty}(x_{n},x)\to0$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon/\sqrt{m}>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n\geq N\text{ implies }d_{\infty}(x_{n},x)<\frac{\varepsilon}{\sqrt{m}},
\]

\end_inset

and since 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{E}(x_{n},x)\leq\sqrt{m}d_{\infty}(x_{n},x)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n\geq N\text{ implies }d_{E}(x_{n},x)<\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset

The converse is shown the same way.
 Therefore convergence of sequences in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 for both metrics means the same thing (with the same limits).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $C[0,1]$
\end_inset

 consider the sequence of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

.This sequence converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 in the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1}$
\end_inset

 but not in the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\infty}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{1}(x^{n},0)=\int_{0}^{1}|x^{n}|dx=\frac{1}{n+1}\to0,\qquad d_{\infty}(x^{n},0)=\max_{0\leq x\leq1}|x^{n}|=1.
\]

\end_inset

In fact the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $C[0,1]$
\end_inset

 has no limit at all relative to the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 To prove 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{n})$
\end_inset

 has no limit in 
\begin_inset Formula $(C[0,1],d_{\infty})$
\end_inset

, not just that the constant function 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 is not a limit, we seek a property that all convergent sequences satisfy
 and the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $(C[0,1],d_{\infty})$
\end_inset

 does not satisfy.
 This will be provided to us in the next section.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Cauchy Sequences and Completeness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremconsecutive})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that for a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 in a metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 to converge, it is necessary that 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x_{n},x_{n+1})\to0$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, this condition is not sufficient.
 Indeed, in 
\begin_inset Formula $C[0,1]$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{\infty}(x^{n},x^{n+1})=\max_{0\leq x\leq1}|x^{n}-x^{n+1}|=\max_{0\leq x\leq1}(x^{n}-x^{n+1}),
\]

\end_inset

To find the maximal value, we first compute the derivative
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dx}\left(x^{n}-x^{n+1}\right)=nx^{n-1}-(n+1)x^{n}=x^{n-1}(n-(n+1)x).
\]

\end_inset

Setting this equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, we have either 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $x=n/(n+1)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}-x^{n+1}=x^{n}(1-x)$
\end_inset

 is always positive on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

, it must be maximized on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=n/(n+1)$
\end_inset

, where the value is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{n}{n+1}\right)^{n}\left(1-\frac{n}{n+1}\right)\sim\frac{1}{e}\left(\frac{1}{n+1}\right)\to0.
\]

\end_inset

Thus, we do have 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\infty}(x^{n},x^{n+1})\to0$
\end_inset

.
 However we shall see shortly that this sequence does not converge under
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 metric.
 Indeed, by the exact same reasoning in the proof of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremconsecutive})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we should also have 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\infty}(x^{n},x^{2n})\to0$
\end_inset

.
 But
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{\infty}(x^{n},x^{2n})=\max_{0\leq x\leq1}|x^{n}-x^{2n}|=\max_{0\leq x\leq1}(x^{n}(1-x^{n})),
\]

\end_inset

has its maximum value at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1/\sqrt[n]{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}(1-x^{n})=1/4$
\end_inset

, which is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 This proves that 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{n})$
\end_inset

 has not limit in 
\begin_inset Formula $(C[0,1],d_{\infty})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremconvergenceimpliescauchy}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a convergent sequence in a metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

, then the terms of the sequence become 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

uniformly close
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m,n\geq N\text{ implies }d(x_{n},x_{m})<\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\lim_{n\to\infty}x_{n}$
\end_inset

, the triangle inequality tells us for all 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d(x_{m},x_{n})\leq d(x_{m},x)+d(x,x_{n})=d(x_{m},x)+d(x_{n},x).
\]

\end_inset

We now make an 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon/2$
\end_inset

 argument.
 For every 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 there's an 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x_{n},x)<\varepsilon/2$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n\geq N$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d(x_{m},x_{n}) & \leq d(x_{m},x)+d(x,x_{n})\\
 & <\frac{\varepsilon}{2}+\frac{\varepsilon}{2}\\
 & =\varepsilon.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 in a metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
Cauchy sequence 
\series default
if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $N=N_{\varepsilon}\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m,n\geq N\text{ implies }d(x_{m},x_{n})<\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{corconvergentinXcauchy}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 is a metric space and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 given the induced metric 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid_{Y}$
\end_inset

, then any sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 that converges in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a Cauchy sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $(Y,d\mid_{Y})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 that converges in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is Cauchy in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremconvergenceimpliescauchy})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Since the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is the metric we are using on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, the Cauchy property of 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can be viewed as the Cauchy property in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,\infty)$
\end_inset

 as a metric space using the absolute value metric induced from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n\to0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, but the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/n)$
\end_inset

 has no limit in 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,\infty)$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $0\notin(0,\infty)$
\end_inset

.
 The sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/n)$
\end_inset

 is a Cauchy sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,\infty)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Corollary~(
\backslash
ref{corconvergentinXcauchy})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 but it is not a convergent sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,\infty)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a sequence in a metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x_{n},x_{n+1})\leq ar^{n}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0<r<1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a Cauchy sequence.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq m<n$
\end_inset

, a massive use of the triangle inequality tells us 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d(x_{m},x_{n}) & \leq d(x_{m},x_{m+1})+d(x_{m+1},x_{m+2})+\cdots+d(x_{n-1},x_{n})\\
 & \leq ar^{m}+ar^{m+1}+\cdots+ar^{n-1}\\
 & <\sum_{k=m}^{\infty}ar^{k}\\
 & =\frac{ar^{m}}{1-r}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $0<r<1$
\end_inset

, the terms 
\begin_inset Formula $ar^{n}$
\end_inset

 tend to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Now if we pick an 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

, choose 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 large enough that 
\begin_inset Formula $ar^{N}<(1-r)\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n\geq N$
\end_inset

, without loss of generality 
\begin_inset Formula $m\leq n$
\end_inset

 so by our prior calculation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d(x_{m},x_{n}) & <\frac{ar^{m}}{1-r}\\
 & \leq\frac{ar^{N}}{1-r}\\
 & <\varepsilon.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Complete Metric Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
complete 
\series default
if every Cauchy sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 converges in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

: if 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is Cauchy in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 then there's an 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Completions exist
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our goal in this subsection is to prove the following theorem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a metric space.
 Then a completion of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 exists.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{X}$
\end_inset

 denote the set of Cauchy sequences in the given metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We say two elements 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n}),(y_{n})\in C_{X}$
\end_inset

 are 
\series bold
equivalent
\series default
, written 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})\sim(y_{n})$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x_{n},y_{n})\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that this is an equivalence relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 The only nontrivial part to check is transitivity: Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})\sim(y_{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{n})\sim(z_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho(x_{n},z_{n})\leq\rho(x_{n},y_{n})+\rho(y_{n},z_{n})\to0+0
\]

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{X}/\sim$
\end_inset

 to be the set of equivalence classes in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{X}$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

.
 Note that there is a natural map of sets 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iota_{X}:X\to C_{X}/\sim,
\]

\end_inset

which assigns to each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, the equivalence class of constant sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $(x)\in C_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{X}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{X}(x)=\iota_{X}(x')$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(x)\sim(x')$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x,x')\to0$
\end_inset

 forces 
\begin_inset Formula $x=x'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We now must enhance the structure of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{X}/\sim$
\end_inset

 by giving it a metric (with respect to which we'll easily see 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{X}$
\end_inset

 is an isometry with dense image).
 We first define a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pseudo-metric
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on the set 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Let's first define what we mean by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pseudo-metric
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
pseudo-metric 
\series default
on a set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $d:S\times S\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 which satisfies the following three properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $d(s,s)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $d(s,t)=d(t,s)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s,t\in S$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $d(s,u)\leq d(s,t)+d(t,u)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s,t,u\in S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The same proof as in the metric case shows that a pseudo-metric is positive-defi
nite (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $d(s,t)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s,t\in S$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The only difference between a metric and a pseudo-metric is that a pseudo-metric
 might satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $d(s,t)=0$
\end_inset

 for some pair 
\begin_inset Formula $s,t\in S$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $s\neq t$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(t_{n})$
\end_inset

 are Cauchy sequences in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\rho(s_{n},t_{n}))$
\end_inset

 is a convergent sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We show that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\rho(s_{n},t_{n}))$
\end_inset

 is a Cauchy sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(t_{n})$
\end_inset

 are Cauchy sequences, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(s_{n},s_{m})<\varepsilon/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(t_{n},t_{m})<\varepsilon/2$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n,m\geq N$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(s_{n},t_{n})\leq\rho(s_{n},s_{m})+\rho(s_{m},t_{m})+\rho(t_{m},t_{n})$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho(s_{n},t_{n})-\rho(s_{m},t_{m})\leq\rho(s_{n},s_{m})+\rho(t_{m},t_{n}),
\]

\end_inset

and implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho(s_{m},t_{m})-\rho(s_{n},t_{n})\leq\rho(s_{m},s_{n})+\rho(t_{n},t_{m}).
\]

\end_inset

Thus, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n,m\geq N$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|\rho(s_{n},t_{n})-\rho(s_{m},t_{m})|\leq\rho(s_{n},s_{m})+\rho(t_{m},t_{n})<\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the lemma established, the following definition makes sense:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n}),(y_{n})\in C_{X}$
\end_inset

, we define the 
\series bold
pseudo-distance 
\series default
between them to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d((x_{n}),(y_{n}))=\lim_{n\to\infty}\rho(x_{n},y_{n}).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The pseudo-distance defined is a pseudo-metric since it inherits the properties
 these from 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{corpseudo}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},c_{2},c_{1}',c_{2}'\in C_{X}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j}\sim c_{j}'$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $d(c_{1},c_{2})=d(c_{1}',c_{2}')$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, the pseudo-metric 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{X}$
\end_inset

 respects the equivalence relation.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j}\sim c_{j}'$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $d(c_{j},c_{j}')=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d(c_{1},c_{2}) & \leq d(c_{1},c_{1}')+d(c_{1}',c_{2}')+d(c_{2}',c_{2})\\
 & =d(c_{1}',c_{2}').
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Similarly,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d(c_{1}',c_{2}') & \leq d(c_{1}',c_{1})+d(c_{1},c_{2})+d(c_{2},c_{2}')\\
 & =d(c_{1},c_{2}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $d(c_{1},c_{2})=d(c_{1}',c_{2}')$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $X'=C_{X}/\sim$
\end_inset

 and define the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho':X'\times X'\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho'(\xi_{1},\xi_{2})=d(c_{1},c_{2})
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},c_{2}\in C_{X}$
\end_inset

 are respective representative elements for 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{1},\xi_{2}\in X'=C_{X}/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

This definition is well-defined in view of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Corollary~(
\backslash
ref{corpseudo})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In fact, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho':X'\times X'\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a metric since it inherits the pseudo-metric properties from 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, and modding out by the equivalence relation ensures that we have identity
 of indiscernibles.
 Note that we also have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho'(\iota_{X}(x),\iota_{X}(y))=\rho(x,y)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{X}:X\to X'$
\end_inset

 is an isometric embedding.
 In fact the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $X'$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, fix a choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\in X'$
\end_inset

.
 Choose a representative Cauchy sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})\in C_{X}$
\end_inset

 for the equivalence class 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\in X'$
\end_inset

.
 Then the sequence of elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{X}(x_{n})\in\iota_{X}(X)\subseteq X'$
\end_inset

 has limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Open and Closed Subsets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we generalize open and closed intervals in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 to open and closed balls of a metric space.
 Throughout, let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 be a metric space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r\geq0$
\end_inset

, the 
\series bold
open ball 
\series default
with center 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B(a,r)=\{x\in X\mid d(a,x)<r\},
\]

\end_inset

and the 
\series bold
closed ball 
\series default
with center 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{B}(a,r)=\{x\in X\mid d(a,x)\leq r\}.
\]

\end_inset

When 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $B(a,0)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{B}(a,0)=\{a\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
bounded 
\series default
if it is contained in some ball 
\begin_inset Formula $B(a,r)$
\end_inset

.
 A subset that is not bounded is called 
\series bold
unbounded
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset X$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
open 
\series default
if for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

 there's an 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $B(x,r)\subset U$
\end_inset

.
 We also consider the empty subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to be an open subset.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
\end_document
